{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17646890","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17646890"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:37:03+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:37:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18214"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18214","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18214"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10928"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73840"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10928","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10928"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18214"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59316"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25401"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25403"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25404"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73840","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/73840"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following statements about bone structure is correct?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Spongy bone is composed of type 2 collagen","Type 1 collagen provides tensile strength to bone","Collagen crosslinking provides compressive strength","Calcium hydroxyapatite decreases bone stiffness","Compact bone lacks a mineralised matrix"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EBone is a dynamic tissue with a complex structure that includes both compact and spongy types. The bone matrix plays a crucial role in providing strength and rigidity to the bone.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe correct statement is that \u003Cstrong\u003Etype 1 collagen provides tensile strength to bone\u003C/strong\u003E. The bone matrix is primarily composed of type 1 collagen, which contributes to the tensile strength of bone.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESpongy bone is composed of type 2 collagen\u003C/strong\u003E - Bone matrix is primarily composed of type 1 collagen, not type 2.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECompact bone lacks a mineralised matrix\u003C/strong\u003E - Compact bone has a mineralised matrix that provides rigidity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECalcium hydroxyapatite decreases bone stiffness\u003C/strong\u003E - Calcium hydroxyapatite increases the compressive strength and stiffness of bone.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECollagen crosslinking provides compressive strength\u003C/strong\u003E - Collagen crosslinking contributes to tensile strength, not compressive strength.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Bone is composed of both compact and spongy types, each with distinct structural roles.","The bone matrix is primarily composed of type 1 collagen, not type 2, which provides tensile strength.","Calcium hydroxyapatite in the bone matrix provides compressive strength and stiffness.","Collagen crosslinking contributes to the tensile strength of bone, not stiffness."],"references":["Khurana, I., Khurana, A., \u0026 Kowlgi, N. G. (2019). Textbook of Medical Physiology_-E-book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Clarke B. Normal bone anatomy and physiology. Clin J Am Soc Nephrol. 2008 Nov;3 Suppl 3(Suppl 3):S131-9. doi: 10.2215/CJN.04151206. PMID: 18988698; PMCID: PMC3152283.","Florencio-Silva R, Sasso GR, Sasso-Cerri E, Sim\u00f5es MJ, Cerri PS. Biology of Bone Tissue: Structure, Function, and Factors That Influence Bone Cells. Biomed Res Int. 2015;2015:421746. doi: 10.1155/2015/421746. Epub 2015 Jul 13. PMID: 26247020; PMCID: PMC4515490.","Cowan PT, Launico MV, Kahai P. Anatomy, Bones. 2024 Apr 21. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30725884."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59316"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18214"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59316","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/59316"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-24T06:02:41+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-24T06:03:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10928"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73840"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving i